Introduction ¶

Dataset Source¶

The "diamonds" dataset used in this study was sourced from the ggplot2 R library. This dataset contains information about the prices of diamonds.

Dataset Details¶

The dataset is about the price of diamonds and contains information on diamonds including carat, clarity, cut, color and price. Additional features included in this dataset are length, width, depth, depth percentage and table percentage. These features seem to be sufficient for an attempt at predicting the prices of diamonds as a regression problem.

This dataset has a total of 10 features and 53940 observations.

Dataset Features¶

The features in our dataset are described in the table below. These descriptions are taken from the ggplot R library source.

Name Data Type Units Description
carat Numeric Carat Weight of the diamond
cut Ordinal categorical NA Quality of the cut
color Ordinal categorical NA Color of the diamond
clarity Ordinal categorical NA Measurement of how clear the diamond is
depth Numeric NA Total depth percentage
table Numeric NA Percentage for width of top of diamond relative to widest point
x Numeric mm Length of diamond
y Numeric mm Width of diamond
z Numeric mm Depth of diamond
price Numeric US $ Price of diamond

Target Feature¶

For this project, the target feature in this dataset will be the price of diamonds in US dollars. That is, the price of diamonds will be predicted based on the descriptive variables.

Goals and Objectives¶

A diamond is an incredibly popular stone that has its own separate industry. For this reason, a model that can accurately predict the price of a diamond would be extremely useful. For instance, jewelers can provide better service to their customers using this predictive model. Similarly, potential customers can use the model individually to figure out the ideal cut, clarity, and size of a diamond. They will be better equipped to understand whether they are being overcharged, provided that our predictive model produces a reliable estimate of the price.

Therefore, the main objective of this project is two-fold: 1) to predict the price of a diamond based on its features such as cut, clarity, etc. 2) which features have the highest impact on the price of a diamond. A secondary objective is to perform some exploratory data analytics by basic descriptive statistics and data visualisation plots to gain some insight into the patterns and relationships existing in the data subsequent to some data cleaning and preprocessing, which is the subject of this Phase 1 report.

At this point, we make the important assumption that the rows in our dataset are not correlated. That is, we assume that diamond price observations are independent of one another in this dataset. Of course, this is not a very realistic assumption, however, this assumption allows us to circumvent time series aspects of the underlying dynamics of diamond prices and also to resort to rather classical predictive models such as multiple linear regression. ("stats_tutorials/Sample_Phase1_Report.ipynb at master · vaksakalli/stats_tutorials", 2021)

Next, we check the data for outliers using the interquartile range. We replace those outliers with 'NaN' as well.

In [14]:
def outliers(var):
    
    q1 = df[var].quantile(.25)
    q2 = df[var].quantile(.5)
    q3 = df[var].quantile(.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    upper = float(q3+(1.5*iqr))
    lower = float(q1-(1.5*iqr))

    count = 0
    for i in df[var]:
        if (i > upper or i < lower):
            count+=1
        else:
            pass
    return count

for col in df.select_dtypes(exclude='object').columns:
    
    count = outliers(col)
    if count == 0:
        print('No outliers')
    else:
        print(col,outliers(col))

carat 1883
depth_percentage 2543
table 604
length 24
width 22
depth 29
price 3532

We observe that there are 156 outliers for carat, 247 for depth_percentage, 52 for table, 2 for length and width, 1 for depth and 314 for price. However, we chose not to delete the outliers as the values are still within a valid range.

The data can now be considered clean.

Literature Review¶

Abstract: Contrary to popular belief, diamonds aren't as rare as people think. There are several factors that affect the price of diamond; however, rarity is not one of them. The price of a diamond is calculated based on its carat, cut, color and clarity, known as the four Cs of diamonds. Other features to consider include depth, table and fluorescence. Market demand also plays a significant role. This paper analyses the aforementioned features and why they are important in determining the price of a diamond.

Introduction:

Diamonds have been considered a sign of power, wealth and status for decades. They were initially believed to be extremely rare and hence had high prices. However, they are actually the most commonly found stone compared to the availability of other precious stones. "More people own diamonds than other gemstones because diamonds are so common." (Moore, 2020)This review will focus on how the dimensions and appearances of diamonds determines its price. It also aims to shine a light on how market demand is perhaps one of the more important factors to consider behind the steep prices of diamonds.

The weight of diamonds is measured in carats. The carat weight of a diamond affects the price exponentially. However, a higher carat doesn't necessarily mean that the diamond will be expensive. The cut of a diamond portrays the shape of the diamond, which in turn affects its brilliance. Lower clarity or differences in cut might change the expected price drastically. "A jump from slightly included stones (SI) to very slightly included stones (VS) isn't going to be colossal. But as soon as you reach the VVS or IF levels, prices start to follow a steep curve and rise in a staggering manner." (Gian, 2018). On the other hand, price jumps across diamonds of different colors aren't as drastic.

The depth of a diamond is the height, which is measured in millimeters. However, the depth percentage is often what is being referred to rather than the height itself. The depth percentage of a diamond represents how deep the diamond is relative to its width. Similarly, table is a percentage feature which depicts the width of top of the diamond relative to its widest point. The depth percentage and table of a diamond varies based on its cut. Similar percentages might make an 'Ideal' cut diamond look attractive while it might be disastrous for a 'Premium' cut diamond. (Gian, 2018) These percentages affect a diamond's price because they represent how light is refracted within the diamond and reach the observer's eye. Since 1999, the diamond company, De Beers, asserted that diamonds are a precious stone by restricting supply. They stockpiled diamonds and created an illusion of scarcity, thus establishing a monopoly. (Goldschein, 2011) Sales were amped up by their well-known slogan 'A diamond is forever'. Diamond suppliers ensured that diamonds were considered a luxury item to portray class and sophistication to prevent the devaluation of diamonds throughout the years (Vaillant and Wolff, 2013). The monopoly has since been dismantled but the perception of scarcity and status remains. Consequently, diamonds are still one of the most sought-after stones for engagement rings rather than emeralds, sapphires or rubies.

Conclusion:

While physical factors play a significant role in setting the price of a diamond, market demand is a feature that must be analyzed intrinsically to understand the various determinants behind the price of a diamond. Therefore, we can conclude that a regression model that can accurately determine the price of a diamond would debunk some of the myths surrounding the diamonds industry, as well as make consumption more ethical. It will also help in clearing out the misconception that diamonds are rare and hard to obtain gemstones that are priced very highly.

Summary and Conclusion¶

Having a precise prediction for diamond prices can have many benefits for buyers. It can help them determine what type of diamond they want for their respective needs. A reliable model would undoubtedly help satisfy their requirements within their budget. Our goal in this project is to investigate whether we can come up with a reliable model for predicting diamond prices using the "diamonds" dataset.

In Phase I of this project, we took on the tasks of data cleaning, preprocessing and data visualisation. We decided to rename the x, y, z and depth columns to length, width, depth and depth_percentage respectively for better readability. We checked the data for any missing values and outliers. We removed rows that contained the value 0 in the length, width and depth columns. We chose not to remove statistical outliers because the values fall within a valid range. Moreover, the data had over 5000 rows so we sampled the data to get only 5000 random rows to save time when running models in Phase II of the project.

This report contains several data visualisations to better analyse the data. Using the descriptive variables we can see that the color 'G' seems to be the most popular among diamonds sold. Carat and price have an exponential relationship and diamonds with SI2 clarity generally have higher prices compared to diamonds with other types of clarity. Overall, premium SI2 diamonds seem to be the most expensive type. Moreover, Ideal cut diamonds have a higher demand according to our observations.

Some of the observations of the numerical data are skewed, including the target feature price. Scaling or transformation will be required to address this issue in Phase II of the project. Carat seems to be the most significant feature in determining the price of the diamond. However, further analysis is required to identify any other correlations.
